is the sheaf which assigns to any &quot;formula_102&quot; the set of branches of the complex logarithm on &quot;formula_11&quot;.

Given a point formula_104 and an abelian group formula_105, the skyscraper sheaf formula_106 is defined as follows: if formula_11 is an open set containing formula_104, then formula_109. If formula_11 does not contain formula_104, then formula_112, the trivial group. The restriction maps are either the identity on formula_105, if both open sets contain formula_104, or the zero map otherwise.

==== Sheaves on manifolds ====
On an formula_3-dimensional formula_116-manifold formula_79, there are a number of important sheaves, such as the sheaf of formula_118-times continuously differentiable functions formula_119 (with formula_120). Its sections on some open formula_11 are the formula_122-functions formula_123. For formula_124, this sheaf is called the &quot;structure sheaf&quot; and is denoted formula_125. The nonzero formula_116 functions also form a sheaf, denoted formula_127. Differential forms (of degree formula_128) also form a sheaf formula_129. In all these examples, the restriction morphisms are given by restricting functions or forms.

The assignment sending formula_11 to the compactly supported functions on formula_11 is not a sheaf, since there is, in general, no way to preserve this property by passing to a smaller open subset. Instead, this forms a cosheaf, a dual concept where the restriction maps go in the opposite direction than with sheaves. However, taking the dual of these vector spaces does give a sheaf, the sheaf of distributions.

==== Presheaves that are not sheaves ====
In addition to the constant presheaf mentioned above, which is usually not a sheaf, there are further examples of presheaves that are not sheaves:
* Let formula_1 be the two-point topological space formula_133 with the discrete topology. Define a presheaf formula_72 as follows: formula_135The restriction map formula_136 is the projection of formula_137 onto its first coordinate, and the restriction map formula_138 is the projection of formula_137 onto its second coordinate. formula_72 is a presheaf that is not separated: a global section is determined by three numbers, but the values of that section over formula_141 and formula_142 determine only two of those numbers. So while we can glue any two sections over formula_141 and formula_142, we cannot glue them uniquely.
* Let formula_145 be the real line, and let formula_146 be the set of bounded continuous functions on formula_11. This is not a sheaf because it is not always possible to glue. For example, let formula_148 be the set of all formula_104 such that formula_150 is bounded on each formula_148. Consequently, we get a section formula_65 on formula_148. However, these sections do not glue, because the function formula_84 is not bounded on the real line. Consequently formula_72 is a presheaf, but not a sheaf. In fact, formula_72 is separated because it is a sub-presheaf of the sheaf of continuous functions.

=== Motivating sheaves from complex analytic spaces and algebraic geometry ===
One of the historical motivations for sheaves have come from studying complex manifolds, complex analytic geometry, and scheme theory from algebraic geometry. This is because in all of the previous cases, we consider a topological space formula_1 together with a structure sheaf formula_158 giving it the structure of a complex manifold, complex analytic space, or scheme. This perspective of equipping a topological space with a sheaf is essential to the theory of locally ringed spaces (see below).

==== Technical challenges with complex manifolds ====
One of the main historical motivations for introducing sheaves was constructing a device which keeps track of holomorphic functions on complex manifolds. For example, on a compact complex manifold formula_1 (like complex projective space or the vanishing locus in projective space of a homogeneous polynomial), the &quot;only&quot; holomorphic functionsformula_160are the constant functions. This means there exist two compact complex manifolds formula_161 which are not isomorphic, but nevertheless their rings of global holomorphic functions, denoted formula_162, are isomorphic. Contrast this with smooth manifolds where every manifold formula_79 can be embedded inside some formula_164, hence its ring of smooth functions formula_165 comes from restricting the smooth functions from formula_166. 

Another complexity when considering the ring of holomorphic functions on a complex manifold formula_1 is given a small enough open set formula_2, the holomorphic functions will be isomorphic to formula_169. Sheaves are a direct tool for dealing with this complexity since they make it possible to keep track of the holomorphic structure on the underlying topological space of formula_1 on arbitrary open subsets formula_2. This means as formula_11 becomes more complex topologically, the ring formula_173 can be expressed from gluing the formula_174. Note that sometimes this sheaf is denoted formula_175 or just formula_158, or even formula_177 when we want to emphasize the space the structure sheaf is associated to.

==== Tracking submanifolds with sheaves ====
Another common example of sheaves can be constructed by considering a complex submanifold formula_178. There is an associated sheaf formula_179 which takes an open subset formula_2 and gives the ring of holomorphic functions on formula_181. This kind of formalism was found to be extremely powerful and motivates a lot of homological algebra such as sheaf cohomology since an intersection theory can be built using these kinds of sheaves from the Serre intersection formula.

== Operations with sheaves ==

=== Morphisms ===
Morphisms of sheaves are, roughly speaking, analogous to functions between them. In contrast to a function between sets, which is simply an assignment of outputs to inputs, morphisms of sheaves are also required to be compatible with the local–global structures of the underlying sheaves. This idea is made precise in the following definition.

Let formula_10 and formula_183 be two sheaves of sets (respectively abelian groups, rings, etc.) on formula_1. A &quot;morphism&quot; formula_185 consists of a morphism formula_186 of sets (respectively abelian groups, rings, etc.) for each open set formula_11 of formula_1, subject to the condition that this morphism is compatible with restrictions. In other words, for every open subset formula_28 of an open set formula_11, the following diagram is commutative.

:formula_191

For example, taking the derivative gives a morphism of sheaves on formula_192, 
formula_193
Indeed, given an (formula_3-times continuously differentiable) function formula_195 (with formula_11 in formula_192 open), the restriction (to a smaller open subset formula_28) of its derivative equals the derivative of formula_199.

With this notion of morphism, sheaves of sets (respectively abelian groups, rings, etc.) on a fixed topological space formula_1 form a category. The general categorical notions of mono-, epi- and isomorphisms can therefore be applied to sheaves. 

A morphism formula_201 of sheaves on formula_202 is an isomorphism (respectively monomorphism) if and only if there exists an open cover formula_203 of formula_202 such that formula_205 are isomorphisms (respectively injective morphisms) of sets (respectively abelian groups, rings, etc.) for all formula_206. These statements give examples of how to work with sheaves using local information, but it&#x27;s important to note that we cannot check if a morphism of sheaves is an epimorphism in the same manner. Indeed the statement that maps on the level of open sets formula_207 are not always surjective for epimorphisms of sheaves is equivalent to non-exactness of the global sections functor—or equivalently, to non-triviality of sheaf cohomology.

=== Stalks of a sheaf ===
The &quot;stalk&quot; formula_208 of a sheaf formula_10 captures the properties of a sheaf &quot;around&quot; a point formula_210, generalizing the germs of functions.
Here, &quot;around&quot; means that, conceptually speaking, one looks at smaller and smaller neighborhoods of the point. Of course, no single neighborhood will be small enough, which requires considering a limit of some sort. More precisely, the stalk is defined by

:formula_211
the direct limit being over all open subsets of formula_1 containing the given point formula_104. In other words, an element of the stalk is given by a section over some open neighborhood of formula_104, and two such sections are considered equivalent if their restrictions agree on a smaller neighborhood.

The natural morphism formula_215 takes a section formula_64 in formula_8 to its &quot;germ&quot; formula_218 at formula_104. This generalises the usual definition of a germ.

In many situations, knowing the stalks of a sheaf is enough to control the sheaf itself. For example, whether or not a morphism of sheaves is a monomorphism, epimorphism, or isomorphism can be tested on the stalks. In this sense, a sheaf is determined by its stalks, which are a local data. By contrast, the &quot;global&quot; information present in a sheaf, i.e., the &quot;global sections&quot;, i.e., the sections formula_220 on the whole space formula_1, typically carry less information. For example, for a compact complex manifold formula_1, the global sections of the sheaf of holomorphic functions are just formula_223, since any holomorphic function
:formula_224
is constant by Liouville&#x27;s theorem.

=== Turning a presheaf into a sheaf ===
It is frequently useful to take the data contained in a presheaf and to express it as a sheaf. It turns out that there is a best possible way to do this. It takes a presheaf formula_10 and produces a new sheaf formula_226 called the &quot;sheafification&quot; or &quot;sheaf associated to the presheaf&quot; formula_10. For example, the sheafification of the constant presheaf (see above) is called the &quot;constant sheaf&quot;. Despite its name, its sections are &quot;locally&quot; constant functions.

The sheaf formula_226 can be constructed using the étalé space formula_229 of formula_10, namely as the sheaf of sections of the map
:formula_231
Another construction of the sheaf formula_226 proceeds by means of a functor formula_233 from presheaves to presheaves that gradually improves the properties of a presheaf: for any presheaf formula_10, formula_235 is a separated presheaf, and for any separated presheaf formula_10, formula_235 is a sheaf. The associated sheaf formula_226 is given by formula_239.

The idea that the sheaf formula_226 is the best possible approximation to formula_10 by a sheaf is made precise using the following universal property: there is a natural morphism of presheaves formula_242 so that for any sheaf formula_183 and any morphism of presheaves formula_244, there is a unique morphism of sheaves formula_245 such that formula_246. In fact, formula_247 is the left adjoint functor to the inclusion functor (or forgetful functor) from the category of sheaves to the category of presheaves, and formula_248 is the unit of the adjunction. In this way, the category of sheaves turns into a Giraud subcategory of presheaves. This categorical situation is the reason why the sheafification functor appears in constructing cokernels of sheaf morphisms or tensor products of sheaves, but not for kernels, say.

=== Subsheaves, quotient sheaves ===
