Here formula_28 is an open subset of formula_277, so that its preimage is open in formula_1 by the continuity of formula_84. 
This construction recovers the skyscraper sheaf formula_106 mentioned above:
:formula_286 
where formula_287 is the inclusion, and formula_105 is regarded as a sheaf on the singleton by formula_289.

For a map between locally compact spaces, the direct image with compact support is a subsheaf of the direct image. By definition, formula_290 consists of those formula_291 whose support is mapped properly. If formula_84 is proper itself, then formula_293, but in general they disagree.

====Inverse image====
The pullback or inverse image goes the other way: it produces a sheaf on formula_1, denoted formula_295 out of a sheaf formula_296 on formula_277. If formula_84 is the inclusion of an open subset, then the inverse image is just a restriction, i.e., it is given by formula_299 for an open formula_11 in formula_1. A sheaf formula_10 (on some space formula_1) is called locally constant if formula_304 by some open subsets formula_148 such that the restriction of formula_306 to all these open subsets is constant. On a wide range of topological spaces formula_1, such sheaves are equivalent to representations of the fundamental group formula_308.

For general maps formula_84, the definition of formula_295 is more involved; it is detailed at inverse image functor. The stalk is an essential special case of the pullback in view of a natural identification, where formula_248 is as above:
