More generally, if formula_333 is a locally closed subset, then there exists an open formula_11 of formula_1 containing formula_272 such that formula_272 is closed in formula_11. Let formula_339 and formula_314 be the natural inclusions. Then the &quot;extension by zero&quot; of a sheaf formula_306 on formula_272 is defined by formula_343. 

Due to its nice behavior on stalks, the extension by zero functor is useful for reducing sheaf-theoretic questions on formula_1 to ones on the strata of a stratification, i.e., a decomposition of formula_1 into smaller, locally closed subsets.

== Complements ==

===Sheaves in more general categories===
In addition to (pre-)sheaves as introduced above, where formula_346 is merely a set, it is in many cases important to keep track of additional structure on these sections. For example, the sections of the sheaf of continuous functions naturally form a real vector space, and restriction is a linear map between these vector spaces.

Presheaves with values in an arbitrary category formula_347 are defined by first considering the category of open sets on formula_1 to be the posetal category formula_349 whose objects are the open sets of formula_1 and whose morphisms are inclusions. Then a formula_347-valued presheaf on formula_1 is the same as a contravariant functor from formula_349 to formula_347. Morphisms in this category of functors, also known as natural transformations, are the same as the morphisms defined above, as can be seen by unraveling the definitions.

If the target category formula_347 admits all limits, a formula_347-valued presheaf is a sheaf if the following diagram is an equalizer for every open cover
formula_357 of any open set &quot;formula_11&quot;:

:formula_359

Here the first map is the product of the restriction maps

:formula_360

and the pair of arrows the products of the two sets of restrictions

:formula_361

and

:formula_362

If formula_347 is an abelian category, this condition can also be rephrased by requiring that there is an exact sequence
:formula_364

A particular case of this sheaf condition occurs for formula_11 being the empty set, and the index set formula_366 also being empty. In this case, the sheaf condition requires formula_367 to be the terminal object in formula_347.

=== Ringed spaces and sheaves of modules ===
In several geometrical disciplines, including algebraic geometry and differential geometry, the spaces come along with a natural sheaf of rings, often called the structure sheaf and denoted by formula_177. Such a pair formula_370 is called a &quot;ringed space&quot;. Many types of spaces can be defined as certain types of ringed spaces. Commonly, all the stalks formula_371 of the structure sheaf are local rings, in which case the pair is called a &quot;locally ringed space&quot;.
For example, an formula_3-dimensional formula_116 manifold formula_79 is a locally ringed space whose structure sheaf consists of formula_116-functions on the open subsets of formula_79. The property of being a &quot;locally&quot; ringed space translates into the fact that such a function, which is nonzero at a point formula_104, is also non-zero on a sufficiently small open neighborhood of formula_104. Some authors actually &quot;define&quot; real (or complex) manifolds to be locally ringed spaces that are locally isomorphic to the pair consisting of an open subset of formula_164 (respectively formula_380) together with the sheaf of formula_116 (respectively holomorphic) functions. Similarly, schemes, the foundational notion of spaces in algebraic geometry, are locally ringed spaces that are locally isomorphic to the spectrum of a ring.

Given a ringed space, a &quot;sheaf of modules&quot; is a sheaf formula_382 such that on every open set formula_11 of formula_1, formula_385 is an formula_386-module and for every inclusion of open sets formula_34, the restriction map formula_388 is compatible with the restriction map formula_389: the restriction of &quot;fs&quot; is the restriction of formula_84 times that of formula_64 for any formula_84 in formula_393 and formula_64 in formula_385.

Most important geometric objects are sheaves of modules. For example, there is a one-to-one correspondence between vector bundles and locally free sheaves of formula_177-modules. This paradigm applies to real vector bundles, complex vector bundles, or vector bundles in algebraic geometry (where formula_397 consists of smooth functions, holomorphic functions, or regular functions, respectively). Sheaves of solutions to differential equations are formula_398-modules, that is, modules over the sheaf of differential operators. On any topological space, modules over the constant sheaf formula_274 are the same as sheaves of abelian groups in the sense above.

There is a different inverse image functor for sheaves of modules over sheaves of rings. This functor is usually denoted formula_400 and it is distinct from formula_401. See inverse image functor.

==== Finiteness conditions for sheaves of modules ====

Finiteness conditions for module over commutative rings give rise to similar finiteness conditions for sheaves of modules: formula_382 is called &quot;finitely generated&quot; (respectively &quot;finitely presented&quot;) if, for every point formula_104 of formula_1, there exists an open neighborhood formula_11 of formula_104, a natural number formula_3 (possibly depending on formula_11), and a surjective morphism of sheaves formula_409 (respectively, in addition a natural number formula_410, and an exact sequence formula_411.) Paralleling the notion of a coherent module, formula_382 is called a &quot;coherent sheaf&quot; if it is of finite type and if, for every open set formula_11 and every morphism of sheaves formula_414 (not necessarily surjective), the kernel of formula_415 is of finite type. formula_177 is &quot;coherent&quot; if it is coherent as a module over itself. Like for modules, coherence is in general a strictly stronger condition than finite presentation. The Oka coherence theorem states that the sheaf of holomorphic functions on a complex manifold is coherent.

=== The étalé space of a sheaf ===

In the examples above it was noted that some sheaves occur naturally as sheaves of sections. In fact, all sheaves of sets can be represented as sheaves of sections of a topological space called the &quot;étalé space&quot;, from the French word étalé , meaning roughly &quot;spread out&quot;. If formula_417 is a sheaf over formula_1, then the étalé space (sometimes called the étale space) of formula_72 is a topological space formula_229 together with a local homeomorphism formula_421 such that the sheaf of sections formula_422 of formula_423 is formula_72. The space &quot;formula_229&quot; is usually very strange, and even if the sheaf &quot;formula_72&quot; arises from a natural topological situation, &quot;formula_229&quot; may not have any clear topological interpretation. For example, if &quot;formula_72&quot; is the sheaf of sections of a continuous function formula_429, then formula_430 if and only if formula_84 is a local homeomorphism.

The étalé space &quot;formula_229&quot; is constructed from the stalks of &quot;formula_72&quot; over &quot;formula_1&quot;. As a set, it is their disjoint union and &quot;formula_423&quot; is the obvious map that takes the value formula_104 on the stalk of formula_72 over formula_438. The topology of &quot;formula_229&quot; is defined as follows. For each element formula_440 and each formula_441, we get a germ of formula_64 at formula_104, denoted formula_444 or formula_218. These germs determine points of &quot;formula_229&quot;. For any formula_11 and formula_440, the union of these points (for all formula_441) is declared to be open in &quot;formula_229&quot;. Notice that each stalk has the discrete topology as subspace topology. Two morphisms between sheaves determine a continuous map of the corresponding étalé spaces that is compatible with the projection maps (in the sense that every germ is mapped to a germ over the same point). This makes the construction into a functor.

The construction above determines an equivalence of categories between the category of sheaves of sets on &quot;formula_1&quot; and the category of étalé spaces over &quot;formula_1&quot;. The construction of an étalé space can also be applied to a presheaf, in which case the sheaf of sections of the étalé space recovers the sheaf associated to the given presheaf.

This construction makes all sheaves into representable functors on certain categories of topological spaces. As above, let &quot;formula_72&quot; be a sheaf on &quot;formula_1&quot;, let &quot;formula_229&quot; be its étalé space, and let formula_456 be the natural projection. Consider the overcategory formula_457 of topological spaces over formula_1, that is, the category of topological spaces together with fixed continuous maps to formula_1. Every object of this category is a continuous map formula_93, and a morphism from formula_461 to formula_462 is a continuous map formula_463 that commutes with the two maps to formula_1. There is a functorformula_465sending an object formula_93 to formula_467. For example, if formula_468 is the inclusion of an open subset, thenformula_469and for the inclusion of a point formula_470, thenformula_471is the stalk of formula_72 at formula_104. There is a natural isomorphismformula_474,which shows that formula_421 (for the étalé space) represents the functor formula_476.

&quot;formula_229&quot; is constructed so that the projection map &quot;formula_423&quot; is a covering map. In algebraic geometry, the natural analog of a covering map is called an étale morphism. Despite its similarity to &quot;étalé&quot;, the word étale has a different meaning in French. It is possible to turn formula_229 into a scheme and &quot;formula_423&quot; into a morphism of schemes in such a way that &quot;formula_423&quot; retains the same universal property, but &quot;formula_423&quot; is &quot;not&quot; in general an étale morphism because it is not quasi-finite. It is, however, formally étale.

The definition of sheaves by étalé spaces is older than the definition given earlier in the article. It is still common in some areas of mathematics such as mathematical analysis.

== Sheaf cohomology ==
In contexts where the open set formula_11 is fixed, and the sheaf is regarded as a variable, the set formula_146 is also often denoted formula_485
As was noted above, this functor does not preserve epimorphisms. Instead, an epimorphism of sheaves formula_486 is a map with the following property: for any section formula_487 there is a covering formula_357 where formula_489 of open subsets, such that the restriction formula_490 are in the image of formula_491. However, formula_492 itself need not be in the image of formula_346. A concrete example of this phenomenon is the exponential map 
:formula_494
between the sheaf of holomorphic functions and non-zero holomorphic functions. This map is an epimorphism, which amounts to saying that any non-zero holomorphic function formula_492 (on some open subset in formula_223, say), admits a complex logarithm &quot;locally&quot;, i.e., after restricting formula_492 to appropriate open subsets. However, formula_492 need not have a logarithm globally.

Sheaf cohomology captures this phenomenon. More precisely, for an exact sequence of sheaves of abelian groups
:formula_499
(i.e., an epimorphism formula_500 whose kernel is formula_501), there is a long exact sequenceformula_502By means of this sequence, the first cohomology group formula_503 is a measure for the non-surjectivity of the map between sections of formula_504 and formula_505.

There are several different ways of constructing sheaf cohomology. introduced them by defining sheaf cohomology as the derived functor of formula_476. This method is theoretically satisfactory, but, being based on injective resolutions, of little use in concrete computations. Godement resolutions are another general, but practically inaccessible approach.

=== Computing sheaf cohomology ===
Especially in the context of sheaves on manifolds, sheaf cohomology can often be computed using resolutions by soft sheaves, fine sheaves, and flabby sheaves (also known as flasque sheaves from the French &quot;flasque&quot; meaning flabby). For example, a partition of unity argument shows that the sheaf of smooth functions on a manifold is soft. The higher cohomology groups formula_507 for formula_508 vanish for soft sheaves, which gives a way of computing cohomology of other sheaves. For example, the de Rham complex is a resolution of the constant sheaf formula_509 on any smooth manifold, so the sheaf cohomology of formula_509 is equal to its de Rham cohomology.

A different approach is by Čech cohomology. Čech cohomology was the first cohomology theory developed for sheaves and it is well-suited to concrete calculations, such as computing the coherent sheaf cohomology of complex projective space formula_511. It relates sections on open subsets of the space to cohomology classes on the space. In most cases, Čech cohomology computes the same cohomology groups as the derived functor cohomology. However, for some pathological spaces, Čech cohomology will give the correct formula_512 but incorrect higher cohomology groups. To get around this, Jean-Louis Verdier developed hypercoverings. Hypercoverings not only give the correct higher cohomology groups but also allow the open subsets mentioned above to be replaced by certain morphisms from another space. This flexibility is necessary in some applications, such as the construction of Pierre Deligne&#x27;s mixed Hodge structures.

Many other coherent sheaf cohomology groups are found using an embedding formula_513 of a space formula_1 into a space with known cohomology, such as formula_511, or some weighted projective space. In this way, the known sheaf cohomology groups on these ambient spaces can be related to the sheaves formula_516, giving formula_517. For example, computing the coherent sheaf cohomology of projective plane curves is easily found. One big theorem in this space is the Hodge decomposition found using a spectral sequence associated to sheaf cohomology groups, proved by Deligne. Essentially, the formula_518-page with termsformula_519the sheaf cohomology of a smooth projective variety formula_1, degenerates, meaning formula_521. This gives the canonical Hodge structure on the cohomology groups formula_522. It was later found these cohomology groups can be easily explicitly computed using Griffiths residues. See Jacobian ideal. These kinds of theorems lead to one of the deepest theorems about the cohomology of algebraic varieties, the decomposition theorem, paving the path for Mixed Hodge modules.

Another clean approach to the computation of some cohomology groups is the Borel–Bott–Weil theorem, which identifies the cohomology groups of some line bundles on flag manifolds with irreducible representations of Lie groups. This theorem can be used, for example, to easily compute the cohomology groups of all line bundles on projective space and grassmann manifolds.

In many cases there is a duality theory for sheaves that generalizes Poincaré duality. See Grothendieck duality and Verdier duality.

=== Derived categories of sheaves ===

The derived category of the category of sheaves of, say, abelian groups on some space &quot;X&quot;, denoted here as formula_523, is the conceptual haven for sheaf cohomology, by virtue of the following relation: 
