<doc id="245530" wikidata="Q5532436" url="?curid=245530" title="Generalized Fourier series">
<text>A generalized Fourier series is the expansion of a square integrable function into a sum of square integrable orthogonal basis functions. The standard Fourier series uses an orthonormal basis of trigonometric functions, and the series expansion is applied to periodic functions. In contrast, a generalized Fourier series uses any set of orthogonal basis functions and can apply to any square integrable function.

== Definition ==

Consider a set formula_1 of square-integrable complex valued functions defined on the closed interval formula_2 that are pairwise orthogonal under the weighted inner product:

formula_3

where formula_4 is a weight function and formula_5 is the complex conjugate of formula_6. Then, the generalized Fourier series of a function formula_7 is:
formula_8where the coefficients are given by:
formula_9

== Sturm-Liouville Problems ==
Given the space formula_10 of square integrable functions defined on a given interval, one can find orthogonal bases by considering a class of boundary value problems on the interval formula_2 called regular Sturm-Liouville problems. These are defined as follows, 
formula_12
formula_13
where formula_14 and formula_15 are real and continuous on formula_2 and formula_17 on formula_2, formula_19 and formula_20 are self-adjoint boundary conditions, and formula_21 is a positive continuous functions on formula_2.

Given a regular Sturm-Liouville problem as defined above, the set formula_23 of eigenfunctions corresponding to the distinct eigenvalue solutions to the problem form an orthogonal basis for formula_10 with respect to the weighted inner product formula_25. We also have that for a function formula_26 that satisfies the boundary conditions of this Sturm-Liouville problem, the series formula_27 converges uniformly to formula_7.

== Examples ==
=== Fourier–Legendre series ===
A function formula_29 defined on the entire number line is called periodic with period formula_30 if a number formula_31 exists such that, for any real number formula_32, the equality formula_33 holds.

If a function is periodic with period formula_30, then it is also periodic with periods formula_35, formula_36, and so on. Usually, the period of a function is understood as the smallest such number formula_30. However, for some functions, arbitrarily small values of formula_30 exist.

The sequence of functions formula_39 is known as the trigonometric system. Any linear combination of functions of a trigonometric system, including an infinite combination (that is, a converging infinite series), is a periodic function with a period of 2π.

On any segment of length 2π (such as the segments [−π,π] and [0,2π]) the trigonometric system is an orthogonal system. This means that for any two functions of the trigonometric system, the integral of their product over a segment of length 2π is equal to zero. This integral can be treated as a scalar product in the space of functions that are integrable on a given segment of length 2π.

Let the function formula_29 be defined on the segment [−π, π]. Given appropriate smoothness and differentiability conditions, formula_29 may be represented on this segment as a linear combination of functions of the trigonometric system, also referred to as the &quot;expansion&quot; of the function formula_29 into a trigonometric Fourier series.

The Legendre polynomials formula_43 are solutions to the Sturm–Liouville eigenvalue problem

: formula_44

As a consequence of Sturm-Liouville theory, these polynomials are orthogonal eigenfunctions with respect to the inner product with unit weight. This can be written as a generalized Fourier series (known in this case as a Fourier–Legendre series) involving the Legendre polynomials, so that

:formula_45
:formula_46

As an example, the Fourier–Legendre series may be calculated for formula_47 over formula_48. Then

:formula_49

and a truncated series involving only these terms would be

:formula_50

which differs from formula_51 by approximately 0.003. In computational applications it may be advantageous to use such Fourier–Legendre series rather than Fourier series since the basis functions for the series expansion are all polynomials and hence the integrals and thus the coefficients may be easier to calculate.

