<doc id="245568" wikidata="Q319913" url="?curid=245568" title="Convex function">
<text>In mathematics, a real-valued function is called convex if the line segment between any two distinct points on the graph of the function lies above or on the graph between the two points. Equivalently, a function is convex if its &quot;epigraph&quot; (the set of points on or above the graph of the function) is a convex set. 
In simple terms, a convex function graph is shaped like a cup formula_1 (or a straight line like a linear function), while a concave function&#x27;s graph is shaped like a cap formula_2.

A twice-differentiable function of a single variable is convex if and only if its second derivative is nonnegative on its entire domain. Well-known examples of convex functions of a single variable include a linear function formula_3 (where formula_4 is a real number), a quadratic function formula_5 (formula_4 as a nonnegative real number) and an exponential function formula_7 (formula_4 as a nonnegative real number).

Convex functions play an important role in many areas of mathematics. They are especially important in the study of optimization problems where they are distinguished by a number of convenient properties. For instance, a strictly convex function on an open set has no more than one minimum. Even in infinite-dimensional spaces, under suitable additional hypotheses, convex functions continue to satisfy such properties and as a result, they are the most well-understood functionals in the calculus of variations. In probability theory, a convex function applied to the expected value of a random variable is always bounded above by the expected value of the convex function of the random variable. This result, known as Jensen&#x27;s inequality, can be used to deduce inequalities such as the arithmetic–geometric mean inequality and Hölder&#x27;s inequality.

==Definition==
Let formula_9 be a convex subset of a real vector space and let formula_10 be a function.

Then formula_11 is called if and only if any of the following equivalent conditions hold:

The second statement characterizing convex functions that are valued in the real line formula_12 is also the statement used to define that are valued in the extended real number line formula_13 where such a function formula_11 is allowed to take formula_15 as a value. The first statement is not used because it permits formula_16 to take formula_17 or formula_18 as a value, in which case, if formula_19 or formula_20 respectively, then formula_21 would be undefined (because the multiplications formula_22 and formula_23 are undefined). The sum formula_24 is also undefined so a convex extended real-valued function is typically only allowed to take exactly one of formula_25 and formula_26 as a value. 

The second statement can also be modified to get the definition of , where the latter is obtained by replacing formula_27 with the strict inequality formula_28 
Explicitly, the map formula_11 is called if and only if for all real formula_30 and all formula_31 such that formula_32:
