Notice that this definition approaches the definition for strict convexity as formula_186 and is identical to the definition of a convex function when formula_187 Despite this, functions exist that are strictly convex but are not strongly convex for any formula_175 (see example below).

If the function formula_11 is twice continuously differentiable, then it is strongly convex with parameter formula_190 if and only if formula_191 for all formula_64 in the domain, where formula_193 is the identity and formula_194 is the Hessian matrix, and the inequality formula_195 means that formula_196 is positive semi-definite. This is equivalent to requiring that the minimum eigenvalue of formula_197 be at least formula_190 for all formula_162 If the domain is just the real line, then formula_197 is just the second derivative formula_201 so the condition becomes formula_202. If formula_203 then this means the Hessian is positive semidefinite (or if the domain is the real line, it means that formula_161), which implies the function is convex, and perhaps strictly convex, but not strongly convex.

Assuming still that the function is twice continuously differentiable, one can show that the lower bound of formula_197 implies that it is strongly convex. Using Taylor&#x27;s Theorem there exists
