A function formula_11 is strongly convex with parameter &quot;m&quot; if and only if the function
formula_210
is convex.

A twice continuously differentiable function formula_11 on a compact domain formula_9 that satisfies formula_213 for all formula_214 is strongly convex. The proof of this statement follows from the extreme value theorem, which states that a continuous function on a compact set has a maximum and minimum.

Strongly convex functions are in general easier to work with than convex or strictly convex functions, since they are a smaller class. Like strictly convex functions, strongly convex functions have unique minima on compact sets.

=== Properties of strongly-convex functions ===
If &quot;f&quot; is a strongly-convex function with parameter &quot;m&quot;, then:

* For every real number &quot;r&quot;, the level set {&quot;x&quot; | &quot;f&quot;(&quot;x&quot;) ≤ &quot;r&quot;} is compact.
* The function &quot;f&quot; has a unique global minimum on &quot;Rn&quot;.

== Uniformly convex functions ==
A uniformly convex function, with modulus formula_215, is a function formula_11 that, for all formula_94 in the domain and formula_218 satisfies
formula_219
where formula_215 is a function that is non-negative and vanishes only at 0. This is a generalization of the concept of strongly convex function; by taking formula_221 we recover the definition of strong convexity.

It is worth noting that some authors require the modulus formula_215 to be an increasing function, but this condition is not required by all authors.

==Examples==
===Functions of one variable===
* The function formula_223 has formula_224, so is a convex function. It is also strongly convex (and hence strictly convex too), with strong convexity constant 2.
* The function formula_225 has formula_226, so is a convex function. It is strictly convex, even though the second derivative is not strictly positive at all points. It is not strongly convex.
* The absolute value function formula_227 is convex (as reflected in the triangle inequality), even though it does not have a derivative at the point formula_228 It is not strictly convex.
* The function formula_229 for formula_230 is convex.
* The exponential function formula_231 is convex. It is also strictly convex, since formula_232, but it is not strongly convex since the second derivative can be arbitrarily close to zero. More generally, the function formula_233 is logarithmically convex if formula_11 is a convex function. The term &quot;superconvex&quot; is sometimes used instead.
* The function formula_11 with domain [0,1] defined by formula_236 for formula_237 is convex; it is continuous on the open interval formula_238 but not continuous at 0 and 1.
* The function formula_239 has second derivative formula_240; thus it is convex on the set where formula_241 and concave on the set where formula_242
* Examples of functions that are monotonically increasing but not convex include formula_243 and formula_244.
* Examples of functions that are convex but not monotonically increasing include formula_245 and formula_246.
* The function formula_247 has formula_248 which is greater than 0 if formula_249 so formula_250 is convex on the interval formula_251. It is concave on the interval formula_252.
* The function formula_253 with formula_254, is convex on the interval formula_251 and convex on the interval formula_252, but not convex on the interval formula_257, because of the singularity at formula_228

===Functions of &quot;n&quot; variables===
* LogSumExp function, also called softmax function, is a convex function. 
*The function formula_259 on the domain of positive-definite matrices is convex.
* Every real-valued linear transformation is convex but not strictly convex, since if formula_11 is linear, then formula_261. This statement also holds if we replace &quot;convex&quot; by &quot;concave&quot;.
* Every real-valued affine function, that is, each function of the form formula_262 is simultaneously convex and concave.
* Every norm is a convex function, by the triangle inequality and positive homogeneity.
* The spectral radius of a nonnegative matrix is a convex function of its diagonal elements.

